Resolutions are soft promises to ourselves. They sound nice, but
they rely on willpower and motivation - both of which are
notoriously unreliable.

If youâ€™re anything like me, youâ€™ve probably spent a tonne of time

column8: Thank you for applying to iCapital - Application Received!
column10:
Hi Candace,

We're excited that you've expressed interest in the Project Manager - Associate / Assistant Vice President role.

What's next? If there's a match, we'll reach out to learn more about you, what you're looking for, and why iCapital caught your eye. In any case, we will keep you posted on your application status.

â€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡Íâ€‡ÍÂ­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­Â­

Hey Candace,

Welcome to day one of the 5-day productivity challenge ðŸŽ‰

So, itâ€™s Monday morning. You sit down at your desk, look at your
to-do list, and... where do you even start?

Monday sets the tone for our entire week. And when we start the
week feeling overwhelmed, itâ€™s hard to shake off that feeling as
the days go by.

But hereâ€™s a secret Iâ€™ve learned: being productive isnâ€™t about
just powering through that endless list of to-dos. Itâ€™s about
designing your week in a way that makes you feel good, energised,
and ready to take on whatever comes your way.

The broaden-and-build theory (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hpr44o7f5h28exlllcn/dphehmu035xlextl/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmNiaS5ubG0ubmloLmdvdi9wbWMvYXJ0aWNsZXMvUE1DMzEyMjI3MS8=
), developed by psychologist Barbara Fredrickson, says that
positive emotions expand our awareness and build our cognitive
and social resources. Simply put, feeling good doesnâ€™t just make
us smile; it fuels us to take action and get stuff done.

So, how you plan your day (and your week) can make a huge
difference to how productive and happy you are.

Thatâ€™s where designing a â€œfeel-good weekâ€ comes in.

But before we dive into planning the week ahead, hereâ€™s a little
something Iâ€™ve found helpful. When I was doing research for my
book Feel-Good Productivity (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hpr44o7f5h28exlllcn/owhkhwurzoe2gkaq/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmVlbGdvb2Rwcm9kdWN0aXZpdHkuY29tLw==
), I discovered three key things that can make all the difference
in how we feel throughout the week: Play, Power, and People.

ðŸ¤¹ 1. Play
---------

I know it sounds a bit weird, but honestly, seriousness makes us
tense, and we rarely do our best work when weâ€™re tense.

Instead, when we tackle tasks with a sense of curiosity and fun,
we start exploring new ideas, coming up with creative solutions,
and seeing challenges as just part of the adventure.

Adding play to your week could just mean working in your
favourite coffee shop, playing your favourite playlist while
tackling a boring task, or trying to beat your own record for how
quickly you can complete a task.

ðŸ¦¸ 2. Power
----------

Power meaning confidence, not control. When we feel empowered, we
stop blaming others or our circumstances and start taking control
of our journey.

Itâ€™s all about knowing weâ€™ve got what it takes to make things
happen.

To infuse your tasks with power, ask yourself: â€œWhat would this
look like if I were really confident at this?â€.

ðŸ§‘â€ðŸ¤â€ðŸ§‘ 3. People
---------------

Ever heard the saying, â€œYou are the average of the five people
you spend the most time withâ€?

To have more energy, we need to surround ourselves with people
who lift us up, who challenge us to be better, and who just make
us feel good.

Now imagine setting up the week ahead not just with tasks in
mind, but also with the people that make you feel energised and
happy.

â€‹Research (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hpr44o7f5h28exlllcn/6qhehou7qo4mndf9/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmNiaS5ubG0ubmloLmdvdi9wbWMvYXJ0aWNsZXMvUE1DNzc5OTc0NS8=
) shows that when we structure our time with intention, we reduce
stress and increase our ability to focus on what truly matters.

Now, letâ€™s put this into action and design our feel-good week:

--------------------------------------
ðŸ’¬ Step 1: Check your space and company
--------------------------------------

First, think about your environment and who youâ€™re spending time
with. These two things can totally make or break your week.

Maybe switch up your workspace for a coffee shop or plan to work
with someone who inspires you.

Little changes can have a big impact.

Weâ€™ll be revisiting this on Wednesday, so donâ€™t forget to
allocate some time to working in a new environment when you start
time blocking.

-------------------------------
ðŸ—“ï¸ Step 2: Time block your week
-------------------------------

Time blocking is just a fancy way of saying, â€œIf you want to get
something done, stick it in your calendarâ€.

But Iâ€™m not just talking about work stuff; Iâ€™m talking about time
with friends, time for cooking, and time to go for a run.

Think of time blocking like budgeting your money. Just like you
set aside money for rent, food, and entertainment, you can do the
same with your time. When you budget your hours, you get more
control over how you spend them.

The way I time block my calendar is by using the Balanced Week
Exercise.

Hereâ€™s how it works:

Imagine your ideal week, with all the activities youâ€™d make time
for â€“ work, exercise, time with family, hobbies, etc.

Then create a blank Google Calendar and block out reasonable
times for your top priorities. For example:

* 8-9am every Tuesday and Thursday for exercise.
* 6-8pm every day for â€˜family timeâ€™.
* 30 mins of reading each night, and lights off at 11pm.

Hereâ€™s how mine looks:

â€‹
The idea behind this exercise is to know how youâ€™d love to spend
your time and what changes you need to make in your actual
routine to get there.

ðŸ”‹ Bonus step
------------

At the end of each day this week, take a moment to check in with
yourself and evaluate your energy levels.

To do so, I like to screenshot my calendar and make a quick note
of how each activity made me feel.

If something in the calendar energises me, I put a + next to it.
If it feels just okay, I mark it as +-, and if it drains my
energy, I mark it as --.

Over time, youâ€™ll start to see patterns, and you can adjust your
week to include more of the stuff that gives you energy and less
of the things that drag you down.

--------------------------------------
ðŸ“¢ Challenge: Design your balanced week
--------------------------------------

Head over to Google Calendar (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hpr44o7f5h28exlllcn/owhkhwurzoe2grcq/aHR0cHM6Ly9jYWxlbmRhci5nb29nbGUuY29tLw==
), click on "Create new calendar," and start filling out your
ideal week. Or, if youâ€™re more of a spreadsheet person, check out
this template in Excel (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/xmue9nmx3rt6hpr44o7f5h28exlllcn/6qhehou7qo4mn0s9/aHR0cHM6Ly9kb2NzLmdvb2dsZS5jb20vc3ByZWFkc2hlZXRzL2QvMUI4S01zdnpyajJvNmRMZHEwYnpnLUlzUHM2TFBtbEhLdDJoTm9xVTlWMGcvZWRpdCNnaWQ9MTI5NDczMzk4Mg==
)â€‹

Once youâ€™ve designed your ideal week, take a screenshot and share
it by hitting reply.

Iâ€™d love to see what you come up with ðŸ˜œ

Tomorrow, Iâ€™ll share how the best strategies to stop
procrastinating on important tasks.

Have a great day!

Ali xx

â€‹

References:

* Fredrickson, B. (2001). The role of positive emotions in
positive psychology. American Psychologist 56(3): 2018-226.
* Aeon, B., Faber, A., & Panaccio, A. (2021). Does time
management work? A meta-analysis. PLoS One, 16(1).

column7: ðŸ˜¬ Time Anxiety & The Importance of Experimentation
column9:
Hey Candace,

Hope youâ€™ve had a good start to February - Iâ€™m back in Hong Kong
this week, after a short trip away following quite a hectic start
to the year with summits and live cohortsâ€¦but ready to get back
into the swing of things again.

Anyway, today I wanted to write about a conversation I recently
had with Anne-Laure (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhn09k4zs6h8rw5000tg/x0hph3uwglvnx7cg/aHR0cHM6Ly94LmNvbS9uZXVyYW5uZQ==
), an ex-Google executive turned neuroscientist and author of the
upcoming book, Tiny Experiments (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhn09k4zs6h8rw5000tg/6qhehou7qd8p0pu9/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL253UHp4MQ==
), which got me thinking a lot about something we all experience
- time anxiety â°

This is the feeling that weâ€™re behind in life, wasting our time,
and just not doing enough. For most of us it stems from
comparison to those around us or what we see online, and if
youâ€™ve started youâ€™re own YouTube channel, or youâ€™re waiting to
start, Iâ€™m sure youâ€™ve experienced time anxiety in this context
too.

In fact, when we think of what it means to be â€˜successfulâ€™ on
YouTube, itâ€™s easy to say things like unboxing a Silver Play
Button, getting millions of views, never missing an upload,
making top-quality videos, and ultimately being able to quit your
job to become a full-time creator.

But this kind of thinking only fuels our time anxiety. When
growth is painfully slow and our videos arenâ€™t going viral, itâ€™s
very easy to feel like weâ€™re not doing enough, because thereâ€™s
this gap between where we are right now and where we think we
should be â›°ï¸

So what can we do about this?

Well, as Anne-Laure writes about in her book, one of best ways to
minimise time anxiety is to move away from fixed, linear goals
and start setting experimental goals. Linear goals might be
something like â€œI want to hit 100,000 subscribersâ€ or â€œI want to
get a minimum of 50,000 views on every single videoâ€ - but
experimental goals, on the other hand, prioritise curiosity,
exploration, and learning through setbacks and mistakes.

Google literally has an entire division called Google X, where
they focus on creating experimental technologies that could be
hugely successful and change the world. Or they could totally
fail, and thatâ€™s ok.

But how do you actually set an experimental goal? Letâ€™s break
this down:

* Start by making a hypothesis based on your own observations ðŸ”¬
* Design a small experiment to test it over a short period of
time (a week or a month is good) ðŸŒ±
* Collect the data, make any adjustments if needed, and then
repeat the process ðŸ“Š

How do you apply this to YouTube? Well, you mightâ€™ve noticed that
weâ€™ve been doing this recently with my own channel - essentially
we realised that weâ€™d not experimented enough with our packaging
over the past 6 months and so we released a few videos where
weâ€™re A/B testing my face vs faceless thumbnails. Iâ€™ll report
back on the results in a couple of weeksâ€¦

â€‹
Similarly, one of the most common questions I get from students
in the Part-Time YouTuber Academy (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/lmur20nw6mimhn09k4zs6h8rw5000tg/kkhmh2ul73084lck/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHR5YS5jb20vcGFydC10aW1lLXlvdXR1YmVyLWFjYWRlbXkvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1leHBlcmltZW50c180MjI1JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jcmVhdG9ybm90ZXM=
) is â€œwhat should I make videos about?â€ or in other words,
â€œwhat's my niche?â€. And these are areas we cover in detail in the
course but it's also something that every YouTuber, at every
stage of the journey thinks about (even I still struggle with it
on a regular basis and have existential crises about what Iâ€™m
making videos about ðŸ˜…), and the best way to figure it out is
through intelligent experimentation.

Initially, my niche was helping students get into med school, but
over time I began to dabble in other areas I found interesting,
like studying, tech and productivity, and my channel has pivoted
in those directions over the last 5-7 years.

So the key lesson from today is to start thinking like a
scientist and designing your own experiments. Not only will this
help you shift your focus away from the numbers, metrics and big
milestones - reducing time anxiety - but youâ€™ll have a lot more
fun along the way too which, as we all know, is key to
sustainable success on YouTube ðŸ˜‰

Have a great week!

Ali xx

world, and takes all the credit.

Now, Iâ€™ve written for 300+ industry leaders including:

* Crypto billionaires
* BioTech startup founders
* SaaS Marketing executives

And I can tell you, Iâ€™ve never had this happen. Not once. The
client has never asked this of me, and Iâ€™ve never offered.

In other words, you donâ€™t have to do original thinking or â€œbe a
geniusâ€ to be a ghostwriter.

Ghostwriting is all about the client and their thinking.

You take:

* Their ideas
* Their stories
* Their insights
* Their perspectives

And channel them through your pen.

column7: Data Teams: Itâ€™s Time to Touch Grass
column9:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/data-teams-its-time-to-touch-grass

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here ðŸ‘‹
I know itâ€™s been a while since I last wrote, Iâ€™ve been completing projects and just got back from camping out in the mountains of Colorado. I wanted to share some thoughts about data the challenges data professionals face even once youâ€™ve been able to put together a dashboard or develop a model.
Before diving in to that, I wanted to let yâ€™all know that Iâ€™ll be running several events in person in the UK, Seattle and Denver. The first will be in the UK, so if youâ€™d like to join me after Big Data London, you can sign up here [ https://substack.com/redirect/2f69e34d-eaa4-414e-8614-b0a03c8b32d4?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]! 
Food and drinks will be provided as well as a live band!
Now letâ€™s jump into the article!
Intro
This weekend I got to step away from my computer and disappear into the mountains of Colorado.
No cell service.
36-degree nights.
Elk bugling in the background.
In those moments, the only thing that mattered was simple, staying warm and dry.
Now itâ€™s back to the data mines for me.
Where I find that many of our professional lives revolve around data and metrics, numbers we obsess over, charts we polish, dashboards we argue about in meetings.
Yet those numbers are almost always one step removed from reality.
Theyâ€™re shadows on the wall, so to speak. A limited reality that often fails to paint the full picture.
In business and data, we often confuse KPIs moving with progress and assume our dashboards and metrics are telling us the whole truth.
So in this piece, I want to outline some of the challenges data teams face when they take data at face value, and how to stay grounded in reality.
Data Is Often A Derivative Of Reality
One of the points I always come back to is this, the data us analysts and data engineers work with is a derivative of reality, not reality itself.
What we capture in our tables, orders placed, clicks logged, tickets closed, are slivers of what happened. We can learn a lot from that data, donâ€™t get me wrong. They provide so much in terms of providing signals.
But they rarely contain the full context of why things happened or how they unfolded.
Some companies have gotten better at stitching together context by joining disparate datasets. But in my experience, most havenâ€™t. Theyâ€™re still operating on thin transactional exhaust so to speak, that gives a very narrow view of whatâ€™s really happening(or perhaps a better reference is the shadows from the cave.)
You can see that sales went up
You can even make a few educated guesses about why, pulling in other thin context sources
But if your only view is the data, your perspective will always be limited
One data leader I spoke with makes a point of visiting physical warehouses regularly. Not because they love forklifts( I mean, maybe they do!), but because they want to see how dashboards, models, and tools are actually being used by staff on the ground. 
Thatâ€™s how they discovered that several â€œdata quality [ https://substack.com/redirect/12e27e89-e790-4f7d-ab29-3234d0dbb5fc?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] problemsâ€ werenâ€™t random at all, they were the result of end-users inventing shortcuts to bypass a slow form. The data looked bad because the system design was bad.
The same pattern plays out at the highest levels. Jeff Bezos once asked a customer service leader how long the average wait time was [ https://substack.com/redirect/5a4265e4-a233-4699-9f91-43204f108abe?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. The answer came back confidently: under one minute, backed by the data. Bezos picked up the phone, dialed Amazonâ€™s 1-800 line in front of his executives, and waited. Minutes ticked by before anyone answered. 
Paul Stroup [ https://substack.com/redirect/67a10afb-733d-44ca-90a0-e1ee934b35d5?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] covered that below in a past post.
When Iâ€™ve spoken with Paul Stroup [ https://substack.com/redirect/67a10afb-733d-44ca-90a0-e1ee934b35d5?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] he often referenced truth-seeking over being data driven. I took this to mean that instead of blinding letting data guide you, you use it to further inform your thinking and decisions. Along with those walks on the factory floor and discussions with end-users.
SeattleDataGuyâ€™s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Metrics Can Be Gamed 
â€œWhen a measure becomes a target, it ceases to be a good measure.â€ - Goodhart's Law [ https://substack.com/redirect/51756431-8aa9-40ee-9374-e3bbde7d31e1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Thatâ€™s the paradox we live with in data. The moment a metric becomes the focus, it starts to lose its usefulness.
Or as one director once told me:
â€œGive me metrics, and I will game them.â€
One example of this was given to me by a test engineer whoâ€™d just retired. Their company enacted metrics for test engineers. In this case, â€œNumber of tests written.â€ Sounds good, until someone writes a dozen trivial tests, checking if the input box can take â€œA,â€ â€œa,â€ â€œB,â€ and â€œbâ€, just to hit the metric. 
I also found this post on Amazon drivers [ https://substack.com/redirect/5ff83f07-13f4-4a46-ad7f-7811bbdb1ee5?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] trying to work around the limitation of how far they can back-up that was being tracked.
A more consequential example comes from the UKâ€™s ambulance response time targets. For years, the goal was: 75% of life-threatening calls reached in under 8 minutes [ https://substack.com/redirect/8ca09a64-4eb6-4839-930b-4889be0b342b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Once that became the number to hit, the system adapted and here is what researchers noticed.
Front-loading to â€œstop the clock - Organizations dispatched a solo Rapid Response Vehicle (RRV) so a clinician could reach the scene within 8 minutes and mark the call as â€œresponded.â€ The metric now looks better, but the patient often still waited for the transporting ambulance to arrive. Net effect: the number improved while time to definitive care didnâ€™t, and operational costs went up because two vehicles were now tied to one incident.
Misclassification inflating urgency - Upstream triage protocols tended to over-prioritize cases into the highest category to avoid risk. That swelled the pool of â€œ8-minuteâ€ calls, spreading resources thin and creating a perpetual scramble against the clock. In some services, this was compounded by â€œCall to Connectâ€ (starting the timer when the call hits the control room), which effectively shortened the window and encouraged dispatching before sufficient clinical information was gathered, raising safety risks and degrading allocation quality.
Sure, the metrics looked better in some cases but it wasnâ€™t actually leading to better outcomes.
Thatâ€™s the trap of mistaking metrics for reality. When we sit in our ivory data towers, staring at models and dashboards, itâ€™s easy to believe weâ€™ve solved something. But unless weâ€™ve really dug into both the data and how the humans systems are actually responding, we might be seeing only a foggy picture.
Counter-metrics [ https://substack.com/redirect/96082488-ebf7-4aa4-80bc-4ae46228af73?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] can help, but they also rarely tell the whole story. The only way to truly understand is to leave the dashboard, talk to end-users, see how the goals are followed, and watch how metrics shape behavior in practice.
Otherwise, we risk optimizing the number instead of the outcome.
Tips for Making Data Work Reflect Reality
Now I am not saying we canâ€™t provide value, or that we should just give up. I do believe data professionals can help the business, otherwise I wouldnâ€™t invest so much time doing this type of work.
But here are some tips if youâ€™re trying to really put the whole picture together. 
Get closer to the business - Donâ€™t just sit behind dashboards, walk the warehouse floor, sit in on sales calls, shadow customer support. Seeing how data is actually created (and how tools are really used) will uncover blind spots youâ€™ll never find in SQL [ https://substack.com/redirect/415f4857-971b-45dd-95b6-cccea88a9817?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. It actually reminds me of when I worked at the last restaurant, weâ€™d have farm days where before our shift weâ€™d spend and hour or two in summer working on the farm attached to the restaurant. Mostly picking the ingredients weâ€™d end up using. It just gives you more respect for the full process.
Collect data that adds context - You can only gain a lot of insights from your core systems. But there are always limitations. Where possible, expand what data you capture or try to pull more in. In the future, I believe more and more organizations will use data sets that are unstructured to provide even more context, better service, etc.
Validate dashboards with lived experience - Build processes where leaders and analysts test the system, call the support line, go through checkout flows, order a product. Treat KPI improvements as an opportunity to dig into the change further. So you improved NPS or churn, great, was that just for certain segments or users? What actually happened?
Combine quantitative and qualitative - Numbers need stories. Include user feedback, frontline anecdotes, and case studies in reviews alongside dashboards. One, itâ€™s great for communicating with management [ https://substack.com/redirect/556d6474-ed41-489e-8ec7-7224cbea9ca7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and itâ€™s what you often see TV reporting do. Capturing a statistic in a single story. Two, it helps you better understand what is actually happening.
Retire or revise stale targets - Metrics that once correlated with outcomes can drift. Review them at a normal cadence. Certain metrics will need to be replaced or retired. They might be getting ignored anyways, so itâ€™d be better not to have them distract from what your company is currently doing.
Final Thoughts
We can learn a lot from the data we have in our core systems, but it doesnâ€™t mean we always have the whole picture. 
Metrics donâ€™t live in a vacuum. People respond to them, policies reshape behavior, and real-world events add layers we canâ€™t fully anticipate. A dashboard might tell one story today, and a very different one six months from now.
Thatâ€™s why good data work isnâ€™t just about finding the right number, itâ€™s about staying close to the reality behind it. Talking to the people who live with those policies, seeing how the systems play out on the ground, and being willing to adjust when the numbers stop reflecting the outcomes we care about.
As always, thanks for reading.
Upcoming Data Events

London Is Calling - Data And Drinks With Estuary [ https://substack.com/redirect/2f69e34d-eaa4-414e-8614-b0a03c8b32d4?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Coffee With The Seattle Data Guy - London [ https://substack.com/redirect/c955fd40-c8b2-4631-8bb8-2171715402fa?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Big Data London(Iâ€™ll be there!) [ https://substack.com/redirect/fb7782ea-b06c-4032-bd64-7340b52d32f1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Small Data SF [ https://substack.com/redirect/11658f71-a90c-447e-8f30-28c45433b1fd?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
Building Uberâ€™s Data Lake: Batch Data Replication Using HiveSync
Uberâ€™s massive 350 PB dual-region data lake, among the largest globally, is meticulously designed for high availability through an active/standby configuration. At Uber, HiveSync plays a critical role in this architecture by ensuring cross-region data consistency, a cornerstone of Uberâ€™s disaster recovery strategy. It diligently manages data replication and synchronization, providing robust protection against potential hardware failures and regional disruptions. This blog post delves into the technical intricacies of HiveSync and its pivotal contribution to safeguarding Uberâ€™s multi-region data ecosystem.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/55feab92-0183-490d-8594-36d95692ab6d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
The Inconvenient Truths of Self-Service Analytics
Self-service analytics is a hoax. A myth. The so-called holy grail.
If youâ€™ve worked in data long enough, youâ€™ve heard that line.
Maybe youâ€™ve even thought it yourself, like the time your CEO asked for a â€œquick data pullâ€ despite you building them a perfectly good dashboard that already answered the question.
When I first entered the data world, self-service analytics was everywhere. Tableau was pushing it hard, then Salesforce bought them for $15.7 billion, and every vendor promised it would free analysts from endless requests.
A decade later, weâ€™re still chasing that dragon.
Now the narrative has shifted: dashboards are â€œdead,â€ or the problem was that Tableau and Looker just â€œnever did it right.â€
Say that self-service is a failure in the wrong room, and someone will tell you, â€œYou were just doing it wrong.â€
Wherever you stand on the debate, I want to explore where self-service has struggled, and what might actually work next.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/1aa11f96-d5a9-4ae7-bf40-367a53ba0eec?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]

column7: Your application - Enablement Program Manager, Sales at Datadog
column9:
Hi Candace,

Thanks again for your interest in Datadog and the Enablement Program Manager, Sales role. We sincerely appreciate you taking the time to apply with us but this role has been now filled.

We make a point of revisiting past applications on a regular basis to match them to newly opened jobs, so will keep your information handy for future opportunities. Your applicant information will always be stored and processed in accordance with ourApplicant and Candidate Privacy Policy ( https://www.datadoghq.com/legal/applicant-candidate-privacy/ ).

In the meantime, we encourage you to visit our job postings periodically for other roles that might interest you at Datadog via ourCareers page ( https://www.datadoghq.com/careers/ ). You can also learn more about #datadoglife from our employees onLinkedIn ( https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/datadoglife/ ) andInstagram ( https://www.instagram.com/datadoghq/ ).

We wish you the best of luck with your job search!

Kind regards,

The Datadog Recruiting Team

PS: If you've applied to multiple roles at Datadog, you may hear from us more than once.

column9:
â€‹

Hey Candace,

Itâ€™s January.

The air is buzzing with â€œnew year, new meâ€ energy.

Gyms are full, planners are pristine, and everyoneâ€™s setting
their sights on their biggest goals.

But hereâ€™s a sobering truth: by February, most people will have
given up.

In fact, your goals have an 80% chance of failure by the end of
January.

* Itâ€™s not because youâ€™re not trying hard enough.
* Itâ€™s not because your goals arenâ€™t important to you.
* And itâ€™s definitely not because youâ€™re incapable of achieving
them.

The problem lies in the way we approach our goals.

â€‹

ðŸš¨ The Motivation Myth

I used to think success was about willpower.

Every New Year, Iâ€™d feel super energised to achieve some huge
goals: study 8 hours a day for med school, wake up at 5 AM, daily
gym sessions.

And sure, Iâ€™d crush it for the first couple of weeks.

But by February, Iâ€™d hit snooze, skip my workouts, and fall back
into old habits.

In hindsight, the reason was obvious: I was relying on
motivation.

You see, motivation is great for getting start, but itâ€™s terrible
for staying consistent. Itâ€™s like a spark - it ignites
excitement, but it fizzles out quickly when weâ€™re faced with
obstacles, distractions, or the sheer grind of daily life.

This realisation changed everything for me.

I learnt that achieving my goals wasnâ€™t about pushing harder or
hoping for another burst of inspiration.

It was about creating a system to take consistent action on my
goals.

)

ðŸ‘€ The System That Changed Everything

Hereâ€™s something Iâ€™ve learnt the hard way:

You donâ€™t rise to the level of your goals. You fall to the level
of your systems.

Think about it.

)
Sign me up for Productivity Spark (
https://aliabdaal.com/spark?utm_source=lifenotes&utm_medium=topline&utm_campaign=dec20standard
)Anyway, in last weekâ€™s LifeNotes issues, I spoke about feeling a
little lost after hitting 6M on YouTube. In this weeks issue, I
want to go into our numbers a little bit more. If youâ€™re an
aspiring YouTuber/creator, hopefully you find some insights. If
youâ€™re not in the content creation space, hopefully there are
still some takeaways about how to deal with setbacks.

Okay, so the thing thatâ€™s been on my mind lately is that our
YouTube channel views are down about 15% compared to last year -
from around 80 million to what looks like 70 million this year.
Same number of videos, fewer views.

When I saw these numbers, my initial reaction was â€œuh ohâ€.
Thereâ€™s this voice in my head going â€œIs this the beginning of the
end?â€ Itâ€™s that familiar pit-in-stomach feeling when you see
numbers trending in the wrong direction.

But hereâ€™s what Iâ€™ve learned about dealing with these sorts of
setbacks. It comes down to three steps that Iâ€™ve found pretty
helpful:

(1) First, I try to actually feel the feelings. Itâ€™s tempting to
jump straight into problem-solving mode or try to rationalise it
away. I used to be terrible at this - my doctor brain would
immediately go into diagnostic mode: â€œAh yes, I observe a 15%
decline in metrics, let me figure out the problemâ€¦â€

But Iâ€™m trying to sit with that initial â€œmehâ€ feeling for a bit.
Not to wallow, but just to acknowledge â€œYeah, this feels pretty
badâ€ without trying to immediately fix it. Itâ€™s like when someone
tells you about their problem and you instantly start suggesting
solutions - sometimes people (including ourselves) just need a
moment to feel bad about things.

(2) Second, I ask myself: â€œHow much of a problem is this really?â€
This is where I put my analytical hat on. Itâ€™s easy to
catastrophise these things: my initial response might well be
â€œwell shit, I guess Iâ€™m irrelevant now, Iâ€™m a has-been, my
channelâ€™s dead and Iâ€™m going to end up broke and homeless and
aloneâ€.

But then I really sit and think about it, often with
pen-and-paper. In this case with YouTube, yes, a 15% decline in
views isnâ€™t great. But does it actually threaten the core goal of
what Iâ€™m trying to do here? The goal was never really about
maximising views - it was about building a sustainable business
where I can have fun, flexibility, and freedom to teach what I
want to teach.

I had a chat with a gaming YouTuber friend recently who went
through something similar. His channel went from getting 500,000
views per video to around 50,000 when the game he was known for
became less popular. Initially, it crushed him. But after some
reflection, he realised that 50,000 people consistently watching
his videos is still pretty amazing. More importantly, heâ€™s
happier now because heâ€™s making content he genuinely cares about
rather than chasing views.

(3) Third, I consider what I actually want to do about it. For
me, that means being a bit more strategic about topic selection
and video packaging (which is the 80/20 of what drives views),
but not overcorrecting or completely changing direction.

Itâ€™s like when youâ€™re learning to drive and you start drifting to
one side - the natural instinct is to yank the wheel hard in the
opposite direction, but that usually just makes things worse.
Small, measured adjustments usually work better.

I think this applies to pretty much any setback in life or
business. Whether itâ€™s a business metric trending down, a missed
project deadline, or realising your new workout plan lasted
approximately 3.7 days - the process is the same:

* Feel the feelings fully (usually itâ€™s a â€œmeh, what now?â€
feeling)
* Ask yourself how serious the problem really is (usually less
serious than your brain initially suggests)
* Decide on a measured response (usually somewhere between â€œdo
nothingâ€ and â€œburn everything down and start overâ€)

Have a great week!

Ali xx
